pull_request.title: Issue: #330 Implement Transaction Management for Atomic Operations
pull_request.body:
CLOSES: #330

## Summary
- Implemented DatabaseTransaction utility class for atomic operations
- Automatic transaction support detection with graceful fallback to standalone MongoDB
- Updated all critical multi-write UserService operations to use transactions
- Enhanced User model with session-aware instance methods
- Comprehensive test coverage including unit and integration tests

## Changes Made
### Core Implementation
- **DatabaseTransaction.ts**: New utility class providing MongoDB transaction support
  - `withTransaction()`: High-level transaction wrapper
  - `withSession()`: Manual session management
  - `isTransactionSupported()`: Auto-detection of replica set support
  - `withFallback()`: Graceful degradation for standalone instances

### Database Layer Updates
- **UserServiceDatabase.ts**: All multi-write operations now use transactions
  - `markEmailVerified()`: Atomic email verification + token clearing
  - `updatePasswordAndClearTokens()`: Atomic password reset operations
  - `generateAndSaveResetToken()`: Atomic token generation
  - `generateAndSaveEmailToken()`: Atomic email token generation

### User Model Enhancements
- **User.ts**: Updated instance methods to accept session parameters
  - `generatePasswordResetToken()`: Now supports transactions
  - `generateEmailVerificationToken()`: Now supports transactions
  - `updateLastLogin()`: Now supports transactions

### Service Layer Integration
- **UserServiceAuth.ts**: Enhanced user creation process with atomic operations
  - User creation + email token generation now atomic
  - Improved error handling for transaction failures

### Testing
- **DatabaseTransaction.test.ts**: Comprehensive unit tests with mocking
- **UserServiceTransaction.integration.test.ts**: Real database integration tests
- All existing functionality maintained with backward compatibility

## Benefits
 **Data Consistency**: Multiple database writes are now atomic
 **Reliability**: No more partial state from failed operations
 **Backward Compatibility**: Works with both replica sets and standalone MongoDB
 **Error Handling**: Graceful fallback when transactions aren't supported
 **Performance**: Minimal overhead with automatic detection
 **Test Coverage**: Comprehensive testing of all transaction scenarios

## Test Results
-  All unit tests pass
-  Build completes successfully
-  Linting passes with no errors
-  Transaction fallback mechanisms work correctly

issue.title: [Feedback] Network Console will be removed in Edge 143
issue.body:
Starting with Edge 143, the Network Console tool will be removed from Edge DevTools with no replacement. As our team shifts focus toward delivering more stable features and improving alignment with Chrome, we no longer have the capacity to maintain this tool. We recommend using the REST Client extension for VS Code for API development and testing.

If this feature is important to your workflow, we encourage you to share your feedback. Strong interest could help motivate bringing it to Chromium in the future.

comment.body:
Lets deadass stop pretending this is about stability or Chrome alignment. If youre killing a tool devs use 24/7 without even a placeholder replacement, youre not prioritizing stability  youre prioritizing your roadmap over real human workflows.

The VS Code REST Client plug? Thats like saying we removed your cars steering wheel, but heres a bicycle helmet.  Context-switching between apps for basic debugging isnt a solution, its a nightmare. DevTools should be a one-stop shop, not a scavenger hunt.

And the maybe Chromium will pick it up line? Bruh. Youre Microsoft. You dont beg Chromium to do your job  you lead. If youre too lazy to maintain Network Console, open-source it and let the community run wild. Dont just ghost it like its a disposable feature.

DevTools used to be Edges crown jewel. Now its just Chrome with worse snacks.

release.body:
## Winget Wingman 1.2.24

### Package Information
- **Version**: 1.2.24
- **Build Date**: 17022113727
- **Commit**: 4e2d7d667dde042c1beacdfc9e016edc2c89eb31

### Test Results
All package deployment scenarios tested successfully:
- Base installations (7zip, GNU.nano)
- AutoUpdate functionality (Notepad++, Everything)
- Version-specific installations (VLC, IrfanView)
- Custom arguments (Twingate, Everything)
- Hash mismatch handling (PuTTY, IrfanView)

### Installation Instructions
1. Download the `WingetWingman-1.2.24.intunewin` file
2. Upload to Microsoft Intune as a Win32 app
3. Configure with your desired WinGet package ID and parameters

### Usage Examples
```powershell
# Basic installation
Invoke-AppDeployToolkit.exe -wingetID "7zip.7zip" -DeploymentType Install -DeployMode Silent

# With auto-update enabled
Invoke-AppDeployToolkit.exe -wingetID "Notepad++.Notepad++" -DeploymentType Install -DeployMode Silent -AutoUpdate

# With specific version
Invoke-AppDeployToolkit.exe -wingetID "VideoLAN.VLC" -DeploymentType Install -DeployMode Silent -Version "3.0.18"

# With custom arguments
Invoke-AppDeployToolkit.exe -wingetID "Twingate.Client" -DeploymentType Install -DeployMode Silent -Custom "\" network=internal.lan auto_update=true\""
```


**Full Changelog**: https://github.com/g0f/wingetwingman/compare/1.1.22...1.2.24

GuardRails provides **continuous security** feedback for modern development teams. ### What to expect? GuardRails scans new code changes as they happen in your repositories. For pull requests, we will post comments whenever security issues are detected. For branches, you will be able to see reports in [your dashboard](https://dashboard.guardrails.io/login). We currently support **static code analysis** and **vulnerable dependencies analysis** for JavaScript, Python, Ruby, Solidity, Go, PHP, Elixir, C/C++ and Java. However, GuardRails can be used on all repositories to identify and prevent secrets leakage thanks to our **secrets detection** engines. We are working on adding support for C#/.NET next. ![GuardRails Dashboard](https://marketplace-screenshots.githubusercontent.com/2860/44305f21-ef07-4a38-b715-ec8a8057aa43) ### What else? GuardRails works out of the box, _no configuration required_. However, if you want a custom experience, please refer to our documentation for the [configuration](https://www.guardrails.io/docs/en/configuration) options. For example, you can already **integrate GuardRails with Slack** to get the right notifications right where you are used to getting them. ![GuardRails + Slack](https://marketplace-screenshots.githubusercontent.com/2860/0c374f72-ba06-454c-a748-532ada0c2807) ## Support If you experience any difficulties or have any questions, you can reach out to us by [email](mailto:support@guardrails.io), on [Twitter](https://twitter.com/guardrailsio) or directly via [our support website](https://support.guardrails.io/).
